      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Shady Side Of the Street</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas Kagan letter on economic value of street trees (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While reporting on the removal of street trees is well intentioned [''The Felling of 4 Trees Removes a Familiar Presence,'' Streetscapes, June 18], you missed an opportunity to educate your readership on the economic impact of tree removal. A street tree adds value to the property near where it resides.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While reporting on the removal of street trees is well intentioned [''The Felling of 4 Trees Removes a Familiar Presence,'' Streetscapes, June 18], you missed an opportunity to educate your readership on the economic impact of tree removal. A street tree adds value to the property near where it resides.</p>
        <p>Many store owners complain that street trees block the view of their signs. However, a properly pruned tree not only does not obstruct the storefront but can increase sales as well. On many a sunny day I have avoided walking on one side of the street just to be in the shade of a building.</p>
        <p>If a street were tree-lined, I might linger in front of a shaded store a little longer. With the foot traffic comes cutomers.</p>
        <p>THOMAS KAGAN  New York</p>
      </block>
